h3. Issue Summary
When accessing <confluence-home>/admin you can see a request is made to localhost:3333 attempting to load atl.admin.js

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Turn on Network debugging in the browser
 # Navigate to the Confluence admin panel via the !https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/files/590259974/590058056/1/1398739558493/Cog.png!

h3. Expected Results
No attempts to connect to localhost are made

h3. Actual Results
A request to localhost is made

By looking at the response you can see batch.js has the following code:
{noformat}
/* module-key = 'com.atlassian.confluence.plugins.atlassian-clientside-extensions-discovery:entrypoint-atl.admin', location = 'atl.admin.js' */
!function() { var script = document.createElement('script');
script.src = 'http://localhost:3333/atl.admin.js';
script.async = false;
script.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';
document.head.appendChild(script); }();
}catch(e){WRMCB(e)};
{noformat}

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

Confluence should provide a health check to confirm if the clocks are synced when using ADFS and SAML.

Huge clock differences may cause SSO issues with the following stack trace:
{code}
Received invalid SAML response: Timing issues (please check your clock settings)
{code}

Installing Companion App on Citrix desktops, should not prompt the following message to every user on start-up though the Companion App is installed and activated already  with SCCM on all clients.
{panel:bgColor=#ffffce}
With Atlassian Companion you can edit files with a program on your computer and then easily upload them again to Confluence.
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary

Confluence may exhibit an error in _*atlassian-confluence.log*_ during startup, generating the support.zip and when we hit this URL in the browser:
 - http://<confluence-url>/rest/auditing/1.0/statistics/database/usage

h3. Steps to Reproduce

The problem was identified by analyzing the *audit-plugin* code in Confluence 7.7.x or later versions that contain the package *com.atlassian.audit.database.usage*. The relevant piece of code:
{code:java}
private final DecimalFormat formatter = new DecimalFormat("#0.00");
...
double percentage = actualCount / allowedCount; return Response.ok(new AuditDatabaseUsageJson(Double.parseDouble(formatter.format(percentage)))).build();
{code}
Note that there's no explicit locale set for the *_DecimalFormat_*, so the system locale is used.

The last line is the problem, it formats and then parses which blows up. Reproducible when changing the system locale and executing:
{code:java}
// Force German locale
DecimalFormatSymbols symbols = new DecimalFormatSymbols(Locale.GERMAN);
DecimalFormat formatter = new DecimalFormat("#0.00", symbols);
double percentage = 79.0 / 7.9E-6;
Double.parseDouble(formatter.format(percentage));
{code}
h3. Expected Results

The calculation is performed as expected
h3. Actual Results

The calculation errors out due to code bug and this exception are thrown in the atlassian-confluence.log file:
{code:java}
2020-10-16 11:15:58,431 ERROR [https-jsse-nio2-10.3.25.36-443-exec-10] [database.usage.rest.AuditDatabaseUsageRestResource] getUsage Unexpected exception :
-- url: /rest/auditing/latest/statistics/database/usage | traceId: 88147af79521bfc7 | userName: anonymous
java.lang.NumberFormatException: For input string: "0,00"
at java.base/jdk.internal.math.FloatingDecimal.readJavaFormatString(Unknown Source)
at java.base/jdk.internal.math.FloatingDecimal.parseDouble(Unknown Source)
at java.base/java.lang.Double.parseDouble(Unknown Source)
at com.atlassian.audit.database.usage.rest.AuditDatabaseUsageRestResource.getUsage(AuditDatabaseUsageRestResource.java:52)
{code}
h3. Workaround
 # Shutdown Confluence
 # Backup {{C:\Program Files\Atlassian\Confluence\confluence\WEB-INF\classes\log4j.properties}}
 # Edit {{C:\Program Files\Atlassian\Confluence\confluence\WEB-INF\classes\log4j.properties}}
 ** Add in this new line at the bottom:
{code:java}
log4j.logger.com.atlassian.audit.database.usage.rest.AuditDatabaseUsageRestResource=FATAL
{code}
 # Restart Confluence

h3. Issue Summary

When the size of the page is set to A4 in *PDF Stylesheet* as per [customize-exports-to-pdf|https://confluence.atlassian.com/conf611/customize-exports-to-pdf-955187090.html] document, Images that are wider than the page, they are slightly cropped in the exported PDF file.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to General Configurations >> PDF Stylesheet, edit then insert the following style
{code:java}
@page { 
/*The A4 paper size is 210 mm wide by 297 mm long*/ 
size: 210mm 297mm; 
} {code}

 # Go to a page that has wide images (for example 1500px) , click on "..." >> export to pdf
 # Open the exported pdf, the images are cropped from the right side

h3. Expected Results

wide Images shouldn't be cropped once in the exported PDF files and should be resized to fit the width of the page
h3. Actual Results

wide Images are cropped in the exported PDF files
h3. Workaround

Reducing the margin to 11m seems to prevent images from being cropped in the PDF exported files:
 # Go to General Configurations >> Edit PDF Stylesheet
 # Edit your PDF style and include/reduce margin to 11mm similar to the example below:
{code:java}
@page
{
size: 210mm 297mm;
margin: 11mm;
}
{code}

From the editor toolbar, choose Insert > Other Macros and choose Jira from the Development category.

We can observe the shortcut description at the very bottom of the window:
 "Select MacroHint: type "Cmd+Shift+J" in the editor to quickly access this dialog."

*However:*
 1. When using macOS, we should use "Control"+ "shift" + "j".

2. When using macOS and Chrome, when we use "cmd+shift+"j", chrome opens the download page (CONFSERVER-27085);

3. Our Documentation does not mention this shortcut:
 [Confluence help - Keyboard shortcuts|https://confluence.atlassian.com/conf77/keyboard-shortcuts-1021226024.html] has no mention of this shortcut;
 [Jira Issues Macro|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/jira-issues-macro-139380.html] does not mention any keyboard shortcut;
[Display Jira Issues in Confluence: more power, more control|https://www.atlassian.com/blog/confluence/display-jira-issues-in-confluence-more-power-more-control] - this blog is the only place mentioning the keyboard shortcut cmd/ctrl + Shift + "j"
 

*We would like that:*
 a) The message should be "Select MacroHint: type "*Cmd/Ctrl+Shift+J*" in the editor to quickly access this dialog." (so Users would know that they should try with Ctrl also);
 b) The keyboard shortcut Cmd/Ctrl + "j" was added at the Keyboard help ( "?" in the editor toolbar);
 c) Our documentation should explain that depends on the key/Operational System/Browser, we can use Command or Ctrl to activate

Once you tab into the search that brings up the search pane, there's no way through the keyboard to get out. Several clients have raised this issue since it is significantly impacting some of their end users. This feature request is to either add a way to deal with the keyboard trap with the new Quick Search Panel, or at the very least disable the new search.
h3. Workaround

You can use custom html to target the search input and then add a tabindex value of -1 to remove it from the list of items you can tab into. For example, you could do this via jQuery with the following code:
{code:java}
$("#quick-search-query").attr("tabindex",[-1]);
{code}
This will enable you to move past the search field with using only the keyboard. Then you can just open it manually with the '/' keyboard shortcut if need be.
